[start section id="20102"]

Metastatic rectal cancer, status-post neoadjuvant chemoradiation, here for advice on further management.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Vickers is a 67-year-old man from the Wabbaseka area with the following oncologic history:
1.  He presented with very mild rectal bleeding (he passed blood about once or twice without clots) and occasional mild abdominal pain. Colonoscopy showed a rectal tumor, near circumferential, at 7-cm with biopsy revealing invasive adenocarcinoma.  CEA was 700.
2.  November 5 CT and November 9 PET scan showed four liver lesions, two of which were PET-avid.  The two largest ones were in the right lobe, 3.1 cm and 9-mm.  Our read shows left upper lobe 6-mm lung nodule (indeterminate) and right paratracheal node (8-mm short diameter -- not meeting abnormal criteria) -- no hilar adenopathy on our read. Both right paratracheal and hilar nodes were mildly PET-positive on outside read -- our review is pending.  Outside PET read said "probable" right hilar metastases and almost certain liver metastases.
3.  November 17, 2009, to December 30, 2009--the patient received radiation to the rectum of 45 Gy with a 9-Gy boost to the rectum.
4.  December 24, 2009--chest CT showed again the left upper lobe lesion, and the right hilar lesions were not reported as being prominent.
After radiation, the patient had one more episode of pink-tinged stool in the toilet (around early Jan 2010), and none since.
The patient has no pain.  He tolerated his chemoradiation rather well, which was 5-FU continuous infusion with radiation.  He has a good appetite.  He is retired.  No weight-loss.

